---
import ProjectLayout from '../../../layouts/ProjectLayout.astro';
import ProjectTracker from '../../../components/ProjectTracker/ProjectTracker.tsx';

const lang = 'en';
---

<ProjectLayout lang={lang}>
  <h2 id="what-youll-build">What you'll build</h2>

  <p>
    A site where you type an artist's name, see their discography with album
    covers, and click an album to view the tracklist and details. All powered by
    the <strong>Deezer public API</strong>, published on your <strong
      >GitHub Pages</strong
    >.
  </p>

  <p>
    The project is the vehicle — what you'll actually learn is the
    <strong>agentic development workflow</strong>: context, planning, phased
    execution, and publishing, all with your code agent.
  </p>

  <h3>Prerequisites</h3>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>GitHub</strong> account</li>
    <li>
      AI-powered development tool configured (Cursor, Windsurf, Claude Code,
      etc.)
    </li>
    <li>LLM configured in your tool (Claude, GPT, Gemini, etc.)</li>
    <li>
      <strong>GitHub CLI</strong> (<code>gh</code>) — ask your agent: <em
        >"Help me install the GitHub CLI and authenticate with my GitHub
        account"</em>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Optionally, install the <strong>GitHub MCP</strong> in your tool — it gives the
    agent native access to issues and PRs. But if it doesn't work, move on. The CLI
    is enough for this project.
  </p>

  <div class="checkpoint">
    <strong>✓ Checkpoint:</strong>
    <p>
      Run <code>gh auth status</code> in your terminal. Your account should show as
      authenticated.
    </p>
  </div>

  ---

  <h2 id="set-the-ground">Set the ground</h2>

  <p>
    Before writing code, you'll create the repository and set up the
    <strong>harness</strong> — the file that tells the agent what the project is and
    what the rules are. Without it, the agent guesses. And guessing creates rework.
  </p>

  <div class="prompt-example prompt-bad">
    <strong>Avoid:</strong>
    <p>"Create a repo for me."</p>
  </div>

  <div class="prompt-example prompt-good">
    <strong>Use:</strong>
    <p>
      "Create a public repository on GitHub called 'deezer-explorer' with the
      description 'Site for exploring artists and discographies via Deezer API'.
      Clone it locally and open the folder in my development tool. Then create a
      CLAUDE.md file at the root with: project overview (static site, Deezer
      API, GitHub Pages), sections for development commands, technical decisions
      (stack not yet decided — maximum simplicity), and quality rules."
    </p>
  </div>

  <p>
    This prompt does three things at once: creates the repo, opens it in your
    editor, and sets up the harness. Read the file the agent generated — it
    needs to make sense to you.
  </p>

  <div class="checkpoint">
    <strong>✓ Checkpoint:</strong>
    <p>
      Repository exists on GitHub (<code>gh repo view</code>), folder open in
      your tool, and a context file (CLAUDE.md or AGENTS.md) at the root
      describing the project.
    </p>
  </div>

  ---

  <h2 id="plan-with-agent">Plan with the agent</h2>

  <p>The project has three features:</p>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>Artist search</strong> — <code>/search/artist?q=name</code></li>
    <li>
      <strong>Discography</strong> — <code>/artist/&#123;id&#125;/albums</code>
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Album details</strong> — <code>/album/&#123;id&#125;</code> (tracklist,
      cover, date)
    </li>
  </ol>

  <div class="prompt-example prompt-good">
    <strong>Planning prompt:</strong>
    <p>
      "Based on CLAUDE.md, create an implementation plan with clear phases and
      acceptance criteria. The site needs to search artists, show discographies,
      and display album details via the Deezer API, publishable on GitHub Pages.
      Suggest the simplest stack that works."
    </p>
  </div>

  <p>
    Read the entire plan. Do the phases make sense? Is the scope clear? Is the
    stack simple enough? If not, iterate: <em
      >"This phase is too big, split it in two"</em
    > or <em>"I don't want that library, suggest something simpler."</em>
  </p>

  <div class="checkpoint">
    <strong>✓ Checkpoint:</strong>
    <p>
      Implementation plan saved in the repository with clear phases. You've read
      it and agree with each phase.
    </p>
  </div>

  ---

  <h2 id="build-in-parts">Build in parts</h2>

  <p>
    Execute <strong>one phase of the plan at a time</strong>. This is
    <strong>Spec-Driven Development (SDD)</strong>: defined scope, validation
    before moving on. The cycle for each phase:
  </p>

  <ol>
    <li>
      Ask the agent to implement the phase (referencing the plan and harness)
    </li>
    <li>Review the generated code — read it, run locally, test</li>
    <li>Adjust what's needed</li>
    <li>Update the harness if technical decisions were made</li>
    <li>Move on only when the phase works</li>
  </ol>

  <div class="prompt-example prompt-good">
    <strong>Example:</strong>
    <p>
      "Implement phase 1 of the plan: [describe the phase]. Follow the rules in
      CLAUDE.md. Show me how to test that it's working."
    </p>
  </div>

  <h3>About the Deezer API and CORS</h3>

  <p>
    The Deezer API is public and requires no authentication — but <strong
      >does not support CORS</strong
    >. This means <code>fetch()</code> from the browser will be blocked. When this
    happens, ask the agent:
  </p>

  <div class="prompt-example prompt-good">
    <strong>Prompt to fix CORS:</strong>
    <p>
      "The fetch to the Deezer API is being blocked by CORS. Set up a CORS proxy
      (like corsproxy.io) so requests work in the browser."
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="checkpoint">
    <strong>✓ Checkpoint:</strong>
    <p>
      Type "Beyoncé" in your site's search. Artists show up? Click one. Albums
      load with covers? Click an album. Tracklist appears? If yes, move on.
    </p>
  </div>

  ---

  <h2 id="publish">Publish</h2>

  <p>Your code needs to be on GitHub before Pages can work. Ask the agent:</p>

  <div class="prompt-example prompt-good">
    <strong>Prompt:</strong>
    <p>
      "Commit all project code and push to the GitHub repository. Then set up
      GitHub Actions for automatic deployment to GitHub Pages on push to main."
    </p>
  </div>

  <p>After pushing, validate:</p>

  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Settings → Pages</strong> in the repository: source = GitHub Actions
    </li>
    <li><strong>Actions</strong> tab: workflow completed without errors</li>
    <li>Visit <code>https://your-username.github.io/deezer-explorer/</code></li>
    <li>Test search, discography, and album details on the published site</li>
  </ol>

  <div class="checkpoint">
    <strong>✓ Checkpoint:</strong>
    <p>
      Site published and accessible. All three features work on the GitHub Pages
      URL.
    </p>
  </div>

  ---

  <h2 id="where-it-breaks">Where it breaks</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>API not responding</strong> — open the endpoint URL directly in your
      browser to test. If it doesn't return JSON, the problem is the API, not your
      code.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>CORS blocking</strong> — the browser blocks direct requests to the Deezer
      API. Use a CORS proxy (see previous section).
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Build fails</strong> — copy the full error and ask the agent: <em
        >"The build failed with this error. Fix it."</em>
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Deploy not showing</strong> — check the Actions tab on GitHub. If the
      workflow failed, ask the agent to fix it. If it's in progress, wait.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Accepting code without reading</strong> — the most common failure. If
      you don't understand what a part does, ask the agent before accepting.
    </li>
  </ul>

  ---

  <h2 id="interactive-block">Track your progress</h2>

  <ProjectTracker client:visible lang={lang} />

  ---

  <h2 id="takeaway">What to take from here</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Context before code</strong> — the harness is the first artifact, not
      the first component
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Plan before building</strong> — an iterated plan with the agent prevents
      rework
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>One phase at a time</strong> — SDD works because each step is verifiable
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Prompts with context</strong> — interaction quality defines output quality
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Read what the agent generates</strong> — accepting without reading is
      the most common failure
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Publishing is part of the flow</strong> — deployment isn't extra, it's
      the natural conclusion
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    This workflow — context, planning, phased execution, validation, publishing
    — is the same one that works in real projects. The scale changes, the
    process doesn't.
  </p>
</ProjectLayout>
